66","Shirley, Derbyshire, England":"Shirley, Derbyshire, England","Eatington, Warwickshire, England":"Ettington, Warwickshire, England","Warwickshire, England":"Warwickshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Shirley","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of the places so named, such as Shirley (Warwickshire), Shirley in Millbrook (Hampshire), Shirley (Surrey), Shirley in Owston (Yorkshire), and Shirley (Derbyshire). The placenames probably derive from Old English <i>scīr</i> ‘bright’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’, though some may have <i>scīr</i> ‘district, shire’ as the initial element if they lie on a boundary; for example, the Warwickshire place lies on the Warwickshire-Worcestershire boundary. The name <i>Shirley</i> first appears in Ireland in the late 17th century, following the granting of lands to a <i>Shirley</i> family in the barony of Farney, Monaghan.","History: William Shirley (1694–1771) was born in Sussex, England, and came to MA in 1731. He rose in the colonial service, was appointed governor in 1741, and was responsible for the British capture of the French fortress of Louisbourg, Cape Breton Island, in 1745."],"variants":[{"name":"Shurley","meanings":["English: variant of   Shirley  ."]},{"name":"Sherley","meanings":["English and Irish: variant of   Shirley  .","Americanized form of Norwegian <b>Sjøli</b> or <b>Sjølie</b>: habitational name from a farmstead named with <i>sjø</i> ‘sea, lake’ + <i>li</i> ‘hillside’."]}]},{"name":"Henry","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["A perennially popular given name, of Continental Germanic origin, from <i>haim</i> ‘home’ + <i>rīc</i> ‘power, ruler’. It was an Old French name, adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain. It has been borne by eight kings of England. Not until the 17th century did the form <i>Henry</i> (as opposed to   Harry  ) become the standard vernacular form, mainly under the influence of the Latin form <i>Henricus</i> and French <i>Henri</i>."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Henry Shirley was born in 1168, in Shirley, Derbyshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Sewallis Eatington, was 40 and his mother, Martha de Ridel, was 32. He married Joanna Clinton in 1193, in Ettington, Warwickshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 1 daughter. He died in 1193, in Warwickshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 25."},"et":{"1168–1193":"1168–1193","1167–1228":"1167–1228","1170–Male":"1170–Surnud","1172–Male":"1172–Surnud","1174–Male":"1174–Surnud","1170–1194":"1170–1194","1191–Male":"1191–Surnud","1194–1277":"1194–1277","1196–Female":"1196–Surnud","1128–1177":"1128–1177","1137–Female":"1137–Surnud","about 1191":"umbes 1191","1196":"1196","1174":"1174","1194":"1194","1172":"1172","1193":"1193","1170":"1170","1191":"1191","1228":"1228","1128":"1128","1137":"1137","1168":"1168","1277":"1277","1167":"1167","1177":"1177","about 1166":"umbes 1166","Shirley, Derbyshire, England":"Shirley, Derbyshire, England","Eatington, Warwickshire, England":"Ettington, Warwickshire, England","Warwickshire, England":"Warwickshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1168–1193":"1168–1193","1167–1228":"1167–1228","1170–Male":"1170–Kuollut","1172–Male":"1172–Kuollut","1174–Male":"1174–Kuollut","1170–1194":"1170–1194","1191–Male":"1191–Kuollut","1194–1277":"1194–1277","1196–Female":"1196–Kuollut","1128–1177":"1128–1177","1137–Female":"1137–Kuollut","about 1191":"noin 1191","1196":"1196","1174":"1174","1194":"1194","1172":"1172","1193":"1193","1170":"1170","1191":"1191","1228":"1228","1128":"1128","1137":"1137","1168":"1168","1277":"1277","1167":"1167","1177":"1177","about 1166":"noin 1166","Shirley, Derbyshire, England":"Shirley, Derbyshire, England","Eatington, Warwickshire, England":"Ettington, Warwickshire, England